    sampleName=sub("\\.txt","",dir("HTSeq",pattern="R[0-9]{1,2}\\.txt")),

2.1.1.1 Normalisation

colData(dds)$tissue <- factor(samples$Tissue)
design(dds) <- ~tissue
vsd <- varianceStabilizingTransformation(dds,blind = FALSE)
vst <- assay(vsd)
vst <- vst - min(vst)

The mean-sd relationship is as expected (slightly higher sd where most genes are expressed; i.e.Â at the average depth of sequencing). The higher sd is unsurprising given the fact we look at many different tissues and conditions

meanSdPlot(vst)

The overall distribution does not look so good

boxplot(vst,main="vst expression",las=2,xlab="exAtlas samples")

2.1.3.1 Merge

merge.vst <- column_to_rownames(full_join(
  rownames_to_column(as.data.frame(vst)),
                  rownames_to_column(wood.vst),
                  by="rowname"))

nona.vst <- merge.vst
nona.vst[is.na(nona.vst)] <- 0

2.1.3.2 Visualisation

How do the datasets look like

plot.multidensity(lapply(1:ncol(vst),function(i){vst[,i]}),

                  xlab="vst expression", main="exAtlas")

plot.multidensity(lapply(1:ncol(wood.vst),function(i){wood.vst[,i]}),

                  xlab="vst expression", main="Immanen et al.")

and in combination

plot.multidensity(lapply(1:ncol(merge.vst),
                         function(i,v){nona.vst[,i]}),
                  col = rep(pal[1:2],c(ncol(vst),ncol(wood.vst))),
                  xlab="vst expression", main="Both datasets",
                  legend.x = "topright",legend.col = pal[1:2],
                  legend = c("exAtlas","Immanen et al."))

2.1.3.3 Centering

To ensure a proper centering, we replace 0s by NA

merge.vst[merge.vst==0] <- NA
cent.vst <- t(t(merge.vst) - colMedians(as.matrix(merge.vst),na.rm = TRUE))
cent.vst <- cent.vst + abs(min(cent.vst,na.rm = TRUE))
nona.cent.vst <- cent.vst
nona.cent.vst[is.na(nona.cent.vst)] <- 0

plot.multidensity(lapply(1:ncol(merge.vst),
                         function(i,v){nona.cent.vst[,i]}),
                  col = rep(pal[1:2],c(ncol(vst),ncol(wood.vst))),
                  xlab="vst expression", main="Both datasets",
                  legend.x = "topright",legend.col = pal[1:2],
                  legend = c("exAtlas","Immanen et al."))

tissue.spec <- expressionSpecificity(exp.mat = cent.vst,
                                     tissues = c(as.character(samples$Tissue),
                                     wood.sample$Tissue),
                                     mode = "local",
                                     output = "complete")
## Calculating tissue specificity

Most genes are ubiquitous (closer to 0) but some are more specific to a given tissue (close to 1)

hist(tissue.spec[,"score"],xlab="tissue specificity score", 
     main="tissue specificity across datasets")

2.2.1 cazymes

caz.t.spc <- tissue.spec[sub("\\.0$","",rownames(tissue.spec)) %in% cazymes,]

This looks similar for the cazymes

hist(caz.t.spc[,"score"],xlab="tissue specificity score", 
     main="tissue specificity across datasets (cazymes only)")

Most cazymes are expressed in all tissues but some seem specific to the woody tissues (keep in mind the apparent limitation of the Immanen et al. data)

pander(table(rowSums(is.na(caz.t.spc[,2:(ncol(caz.t.spc)-2)]))))

The cazymes appear slightly more tissue specific that all genes

a.sel <- !is.na(tissue.spec[,"score"])
c.sel <- !is.na(caz.t.spc[,"score"])
plot.multidensity(list(all=tissue.spec[a.sel,"score"],
                       cazymes=caz.t.spc[c.sel,"score"]),
                       col=pal[1:2],xlab="tissue specificity score",
                  lwd=2)

The difference in the means is small but significant

t.test(tissue.spec[! rownames(tissue.spec) %in% rownames(caz.t.spc),"score"],caz.t.spc[,"score"])

##  Welch Two Sample t-test

2.2.2 Ordering

dat <- apply(tissue.spec[,2:(ncol(caz.t.spc)-2)] == tissue.spec[,"maxn"],1,which)

We need to handle the cases were we have NA

exp.peak <- colnames(tissue.spec[,2:(ncol(caz.t.spc)-2)])[sapply(dat,"[",1)]

ord <- order(exp.peak,(1-tissue.spec[,"score"]))

caz.peak <- exp.peak[sub("\\.0$","",rownames(tissue.spec)) %in% cazymes]
caz.ord <- order(caz.peak,
                 (1-caz.t.spc [,"score"]))

Export

write.csv(cbind(tissue.spec,exp.peak)[ord,],
          file="All_vst-expression-data_expression-specificity-order.csv")

Export

write.csv(cbind(caz.t.spc,caz.peak)[caz.ord,],
          file="cazymes-tissue-specificity.csv")

3 Heatmaps

3.1 Expression values

3.1.1 Z-score, pearson distance, ward correlation

Here we need to keep in mind that both datasets are not immediately comparable

sel <- sub("\\.0$","",rownames(nona.cent.vst)) %in% cazymes
dat <- nona.cent.vst[sel,]
s.dat <- t(scale(t(dat)))
n.sel <- rowSums(is.na(s.dat)) != ncol(s.dat)
heatmap.2(s.dat[n.sel,],distfun = pearson.dist, 
          hclustfun = function(X){hclust(X,method = "ward.D")},
          ColSideColors = cpal[as.integer(factor(c(as.character(samples$Tissue),
                                                  wood.sample$Tissue)))],
          RowSideColors = cpal[as.integer(factor(exp.peak[sel][n.sel]))],
          trace="none",col=hpal,labRow = NA,labCol = c(as.character(samples$SampleID),
                                                         wood.sample$Tissue))

3.2 Tissue specificity

caz.prop <- caz.t.spc[,2:(ncol(caz.t.spc)-2)]/rowSums(caz.t.spc[,2:(ncol(caz.t.spc)-2)],na.rm=TRUE)
caz.prop[is.na(caz.prop)] <- 0

Most cazymes are ubiquitously expressed but some are tissue specific, obviously in the wood tissue, but also in the seeds

labels <- colnames(caz.t.spc)[2:(ncol(caz.t.spc)-2)]
newLabs <- as.character(samples$SampleID)[match(labels,samples$Tissue)]
labels[!is.na(newLabs)] <- newLabs[!is.na(newLabs)]

heatmap.2(caz.prop[caz.ord,],trace="none",
          ColSideColors = cpal[as.integer(factor(colnames(caz.t.spc)[2:(ncol(caz.t.spc)-2)]))],
          RowSideColors = cpal[as.integer(factor(caz.peak[caz.ord]))],
          labCol = labels,col=hpal10,
          labRow = NA)
